The calculation of emissions from the consumption of intermittent low-use fluorinated GHGs involves using default utilization and by-product formation rates as specified in paragraph (i)(4) of this section. If a fluorinated GHG was not used during stack testing and does not meet the definition of intermittent low-use fluorinated GHG, then the stack systems associated with the use of that gas must be tested at a time when the gas is in use at a magnitude that allows the determination of an emission factor according to the procedures specified in paragraph (i)(3) of this section. Additionally, a planned analysis of the effect on overall facility emissions using a representative gas-use profile for a 200 mm, 300 mm, or 450 mm fab is required. If default emission factors are not available for a particular input gas and process type or sub-type combination, utilization and by-product formation rates of zero must be used along with Equations I–8 and I–9 of this subpart. Furthermore, the development of apportioning factors for fluorinated GHG and N2O consumption is necessary, along with adherence to QA/QC procedures when calculating annual gas consumption for each fluorinated GHG and N2O used at each fab and emissions from the use of each fluorinated heat transfer fluid on a fab basis.{
